# React + TypeScript + Vite — Cursor Rules

## Project Stack
- React 19, TypeScript, Vite
- Styling: CSS Modules (default) or Tailwind if added
- No UI lib unless explicitly installed

---

## Folder Structure

```
src/
├── assets/             # Static files: images, fonts, svgs
├── components/         # Globally reusable UI components
│   └── ui/             # Primitive components: Button, Input, Modal, Badge, etc.
├── features/           # Feature-scoped modules (self-contained)
│   └── [feature]/
│       ├── components/ # Feature-specific components
│       ├── hooks/      # Feature-specific hooks
│       ├── services/   # Feature-specific API calls
│       ├── store/      # Feature-specific state
│       └── types.ts    # Feature-specific types
├── hooks/              # Shared custom hooks (useDebounce, useLocalStorage, etc.)
├── layouts/            # Route layout wrappers (AppLayout, AuthLayout)
├── lib/                # Third-party setup/config (axios instance, queryClient, etc.)
├── pages/              # One file per route; thin — just compose features/layouts
├── services/           # Global API layer: base client + shared endpoint functions
├── store/              # Global state (Zustand slices or React Context)
├── types/              # Global TS types, interfaces, enums
└── utils/              # Pure functions, no side effects
    ├── format.ts       # Date, number, string formatters
    ├── validation.ts   # Input validators
    ├── constants.ts    # App-wide constants
    └── helpers.ts      # Misc utility functions
```

---

## Component Rules

- One component per file. Filename = component name (PascalCase).
- Co-locate the component's CSS Module in the same folder: `Button.tsx` + `Button.module.css`.
- Props interface always named `[ComponentName]Props` and defined in the same file.
- Prefer named exports for components. Default export only for pages/routes.
- Never put business logic directly in JSX — extract to a hook or util.
- Keep components under ~150 lines. Split when they grow beyond this.
- Avoid boolean prop names that read ambiguously — prefer `isLoading` over `loading`.

```tsx
// Good
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  isLoading?: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
}

export function Button({ label, isLoading = false, onClick }: ButtonProps) {
  return (
    <button onClick={onClick} disabled={isLoading}>
      {isLoading ? 'Loading...' : label}
    </button>
  );
}
```

---

## Custom Hooks Rules

- All custom hooks live in `src/hooks/` (shared) or `features/[x]/hooks/` (scoped).
- Filename: `use[Name].ts` — always prefixed with `use`.
- A hook must do one thing. If it does two, split it.
- Return a plain object `{ value, setValue }` — not a positional array unless it mirrors React's pattern.
- Never fetch data directly in a component — use a hook (`useUsers`, `useProduct`).

---

## Services / API Layer Rules

- All HTTP calls live in `src/services/` or `features/[x]/services/`.
- Create a base Axios (or fetch wrapper) instance in `src/lib/api.ts`.
- Each service file maps to one resource: `userService.ts`, `productService.ts`.
- Service functions are plain async functions — they do not touch state.
- Never call `fetch`/`axios` directly inside a component or hook body.

```ts
// src/services/userService.ts
import { api } from '@/lib/api';
import type { User } from '@/types/user';

export async function getUsers(): Promise<User[]> {
  const { data } = await api.get('/users');
  return data;
}

export async function getUserById(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const { data } = await api.get(`/users/${id}`);
  return data;
}
```

---

## TypeScript Rules

- No `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow it.
- All function parameters and return types must be typed.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections.
- Global shared types go in `src/types/`. Feature types stay in `features/[x]/types.ts`.
- Use path aliases: `@/` maps to `src/`. Never use deep relative paths like `../../../`.

---

## Utils Rules

- Utils are pure functions — no side effects, no imports from React.
- Group by concern: `format.ts`, `validation.ts`, `helpers.ts`, `constants.ts`.
- Every util function must be individually exported (named export).
- Test utils in isolation — they should be trivially unit-testable.

```ts
// src/utils/format.ts
export function formatCurrency(amount: number, currency = 'USD'): string {
  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency }).format(amount);
}

export function formatDate(date: Date | string, locale = 'en-US'): string {
  return new Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale).format(new Date(date));
}
```

---

## State Management Rules

- Local UI state: `useState` / `useReducer` inside the component or hook.
- Shared feature state: Zustand slice in `features/[x]/store/` or `src/store/`.
- Server state (async data): React Query / SWR in hooks — do not duplicate in global store.
- Never store derived data — compute it from source truth.
- Never put server responses directly into global state without normalization.

---

## Pages Rules

- Pages are thin — they compose layouts, features, and pass route params.
- No business logic, no direct API calls, no raw JSX building in pages.
- One file per route. Named after the route: `UsersPage.tsx`, `ProductDetailPage.tsx`.

---

## Naming Conventions

| Thing              | Convention         | Example                  |
|--------------------|--------------------|--------------------------|
| Component files    | PascalCase         | `UserCard.tsx`           |
| Hook files         | camelCase          | `useUserData.ts`         |
| Service files      | camelCase          | `userService.ts`         |
| Util files         | camelCase          | `format.ts`              |
| Type/Interface     | PascalCase         | `UserProfile`            |
| Constants          | SCREAMING_SNAKE    | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`        |
| CSS Modules        | camelCase classes  | `styles.cardWrapper`     |
| Zustand stores     | camelCase          | `useAuthStore.ts`        |

---

## Imports Order (enforce with ESLint)

1. React and React ecosystem
2. Third-party libraries
3. Internal absolute imports (`@/...`)
4. Relative imports (`./...`)
5. Type imports (last)

---

## What to Avoid

- No barrel files (`index.ts` that re-exports everything) unless the folder is a published package boundary.
- No prop drilling more than 2 levels — lift state or use context/store.
- No inline styles — use CSS Modules or utility classes.
- No `useEffect` for derived state — compute inline or with `useMemo`.
- No God components — if a component takes more than 7 props, decompose it.
- No hardcoded strings in JSX — use constants or i18n keys.
